          "Based on the imaging findings, the patient presents with a large primary lung mass in the right upper lobe with involvement of regional lymph nodes (hilar and mediastinal).  There is no evidence of distant metastases.  This imaging profile is most consistent with **Stage IIIA Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer (NSCLC)** according to the 8th edition TNM staging system.  However, this is a preliminary assessment pending histopathological confirmation of the diagnosis and precise nodal staging which requires tissue sampling and potentially mediastinoscopy or endobronchial ultrasound-guided transbronchial needle aspiration (EBUS-TBNA).",
          "The primary lesion is located in the right upper lobe, close to the hilum and major vessels. The extent of lymph node involvement needs further clarification through invasive procedures to determine the exact N category. The close proximity of the tumor to major vessels could influence surgical resectability. The mild emphysema might impact surgical planning and post-operative recovery."
